ation, predatory pricing, and intellectual property. After identifying how prevailing analyses differ across these areas, they then examine the policy ramifications. Several themes run throughout the book, including differences in the amount of discretion firms have in dealing with purchasers, the weight given to the welfare of various market participants, and whether competition tends to be viewed as an efficiency-generating process or as rivalry. The authors conclude with forecasts and suggestions for how greater compatibility might ultimately be attained.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh  acomparative law, military, european union, united states, big business, finance, money, wealth, power, eu competition policy, marketplace, free markets, trade, commerce, antitrust decisions, social values, political institutions, legal precedent, language, mergers, price discrimination, predatory pricing, intellectual property, purchasers, welfare, monopolization, judicial review, supply contracts, single-product loyalty.1 aKudrle, Robert T., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106904390 cprintz978022617610940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226176246423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226176246/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles